public void setCursorLocation (int x, int y) {
              checkDevice ();
              /* This is not supported on GTK */
       }

Bug.WithStack:
There is no way to move a node in a GEF diagram exclusively through the
keyboard on LINUX.  We have observed this on SUSE Server v9.0 and REDHAT v3.0
both running GTK 2.2.1.

On Windows, this capability is available by navigating to a node using the
arrow keys, and then using the '.' or '>' key to select a "handle" for the node
and then using the arrow keys to move that node around.  This behavior can be
observed using the Logic GEF sample.

On Windows the underlying method on the OS class which performs the work is:

       public void setCursorLocation (int x, int y) {
              checkDevice ();
              OS.SetCursorPos (x, y);
       }

On LINUX it's:

       public void setCursorLocation (int x, int y) {
              checkDevice ();
              /* This is not supported on GTK */
       }

The call that GEF makes to move the cursor has no underlying implementation.

Is there another mechanism that GEF can use to achieve the desired results?
The only platform with accessibility support is win32. Perhaps GTK support has 
improved since that comment was written. Routing to SWT for comment.
For 3.1, we went behind GTK+ and started calling XWarpPointer to implement this
particular call.

Randy, I'm not sure what you mean by "accessibility support", there are lots of
a11y features in GTK+.

*** This bug has been marked as a duplicate of 70620 ***

