public class TableError {
	
   private static Table table1;
   private static Table table2;

   public static void main(String[] args) {
      Display display = new Display();
      Shell whelk = new Shell(display);
	
      GridLayout grid = new GridLayout(2,false);
      whelk.setLayout(grid);

  // NOTE: Try to remove SWT.BORDER and a scrollbar of incorrect proportions  
  // appears in the second table.  
      table1 = new Table(whelk, SWT.SINGLE | SWT.BORDER | SWT.FULL_SELECTION );
	
  // NOTE: Change to GridData.FILL_BOTH and scrollbars appear.  
      GridData data = new GridData(GridData.VERTICAL_ALIGN_BEGINNING);    
      table1.setLayoutData(data);
      table1.setHeaderVisible(true);
	
      TableColumn[] columns = new TableColumn[7];
      for (int i=0, n = 7; i < n; i++) {
         TableColumn next = new TableColumn(table1,SWT.TRAIL);
         next.setText("Column "+i);
         columns[i] = next;
      }
	
      for(int i=0;i<20;i++) {
         TableItem item = new TableItem(table1, SWT.NONE);
	 for(int c = 0;c<7;c++) item.setText(c, "Data "+i);
      }
		
      for (int i=0; i < 7; i++) {
         columns[i].pack();
      }
	
      table2 = new Table(whelk,SWT.SINGLE | SWT.BORDER | SWT.FULL_SELECTION );
      GridData data2 = new GridData(GridData.FILL_BOTH);
      table2.setLayoutData(data2);
      table2.setHeaderVisible(true);
	
      for (int i=0, n = 7; i < n; i++) {
         TableColumn next = new TableColumn(table2,SWT.TRAIL);
         next.setText("Column "+i);
         columns[i] = next;
      }
		
      for(int i=0;i<20;i++) {
         TableItem item = new TableItem(table2, SWT.NONE);
         for(int c = 0;c<7;c++) item.setText(c, "Data "+i);
      }
		
      for (int i=0; i < 7; i++) {
         columns[i].pack();
      }
		
      whelk.open();
      while (!whelk.isDisposed()) {
         if(!display.readAndDispatch()) {
            display.sleep();
         }
      }
      display.dispose();
   }
}

Bug.WithStack:
Use of GridData.VERTICAL_ALIGN_BEGINNING for a table's layout data will inhibit
the use of a scrollbar on any other table in that shell, even if the later table
uses GridData.FILL_BOTH.  

The following code worked well on Eclipse 3.0, whereas now it fails to function
properly.  
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

import org.eclipse.swt.SWT;
import org.eclipse.swt.layout.GridData;
import org.eclipse.swt.layout.GridLayout;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Display;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Shell;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Table;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.TableColumn;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.TableItem;

public class TableError {
	
   private static Table table1;
   private static Table table2;

   public static void main(String[] args) {
      Display display = new Display();
      Shell whelk = new Shell(display);
	
      GridLayout grid = new GridLayout(2,false);
      whelk.setLayout(grid);

  // NOTE: Try to remove SWT.BORDER and a scrollbar of incorrect proportions  
  // appears in the second table.  
      table1 = new Table(whelk, SWT.SINGLE | SWT.BORDER | SWT.FULL_SELECTION );
	
  // NOTE: Change to GridData.FILL_BOTH and scrollbars appear.  
      GridData data = new GridData(GridData.VERTICAL_ALIGN_BEGINNING);    
      table1.setLayoutData(data);
      table1.setHeaderVisible(true);
	
      TableColumn[] columns = new TableColumn[7];
      for (int i=0, n = 7; i < n; i++) {
         TableColumn next = new TableColumn(table1,SWT.TRAIL);
         next.setText("Column "+i);
         columns[i] = next;
      }
	
      for(int i=0;i<20;i++) {
         TableItem item = new TableItem(table1, SWT.NONE);
	 for(int c = 0;c<7;c++) item.setText(c, "Data "+i);
      }
		
      for (int i=0; i < 7; i++) {
         columns[i].pack();
      }
	
      table2 = new Table(whelk,SWT.SINGLE | SWT.BORDER | SWT.FULL_SELECTION );
      GridData data2 = new GridData(GridData.FILL_BOTH);
      table2.setLayoutData(data2);
      table2.setHeaderVisible(true);
	
      for (int i=0, n = 7; i < n; i++) {
         TableColumn next = new TableColumn(table2,SWT.TRAIL);
         next.setText("Column "+i);
         columns[i] = next;
      }
		
      for(int i=0;i<20;i++) {
         TableItem item = new TableItem(table2, SWT.NONE);
         for(int c = 0;c<7;c++) item.setText(c, "Data "+i);
      }
		
      for (int i=0; i < 7; i++) {
         columns[i].pack();
      }
		
      whelk.open();
      while (!whelk.isDisposed()) {
         if(!display.readAndDispatch()) {
            display.sleep();
         }
      }
      display.dispose();
   }
}
Since the GridData field grabExcessVerticalSpace is false for the left table,
the table will be laid out at its preferred height, and the height of the
left cell will never go below that value. This also means that the height
of the entire row (including the right cell) will not go below that value.
The right table is thus prevented from becoming less tall, and that's why
you don't get a vertical scroll bar. I think this is the expected behaviour.
I agree with Florian.

